'''Moussa Niakhaté''' (born 8 March 1996) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for {{French football updater|Lyon}} club [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]].

==Club career==

===Valenciennes===
On 20 October 2014, he made his professional debut for [[Valenciennes FC|Valenciennes]] in a home match against [[Dijon FCO|Dijon]]. On 1 July 2015, he signed his first professional contract with Valenciennes, a three-year deal.

For the 2016–17 season, [[Faruk Hadžibegić]] made him one of the key players in his squad.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=28 June 2024 |title=Ligue 2 - VAFC : Élève assidu, Moussa Niakhaté apprend vite à Valenciennes |url=https://www.lavoixdunord.fr/37842/article/2016-08-25/ligue-2-vafc-eleve-assidu-moussa-niakhate-apprend-vite-valenciennes |url-access=subscription |website=[[La Voix du Nord]]}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> On 19 December 2016, he scored his first goal in an away match against [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]].

===Metz===
On 22 June 2017, he joined [[FC Metz|Metz]] on a four-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=28 June 2024 |author=Ch. J. |date=22 June 2017 |title=Football : Moussa Niakhaté débarque au FC Metz |url=https://www.republicain-lorrain.fr/sports/2017/06/22/moussa-niakhate-debarque-en-moselle |website=[[Le Républicain lorrain]]}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> He quickly established himself as a promising young player<ref>{{cite web|access-date=2025-02-01 |date=2018-07-07 |language=fr |last=sgobbi |title=Moussa Niakhaté rejoint la Bundesliga ! |url=https://www.fcmetz.com/2018-2019/actualites/equipe-pro/moussa-niakhate-rejoint-la-bundesliga |website=Football Club de Metz}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> and was called up several times to the [[France national under-21 football team|France under-21 team]] by [[Sylvain Ripoll]]. At Metz, he became an undisputed starter and a key figure in the club’s central defense. During the 2017–18 season, he made 35 appearances and provided an assist in a match against [[Montpellier HSC]] in December 2017.

===Mainz 05===
His season allowed him to sign with [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz]] on 7 July 2018 for a fee of €10 million plus bonuses.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=8 July 2018 |date=7 July 2018 |title=Moussa Niakhaté à Mayence (officiel) |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Moussa-niakhate-a-mayence-officiel/920406  |website=[[L'Équipe]]}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

After wearing the captain's armband several times between 2019 and 2021 whenever the captain [[Danny Latza]] was absent, he became the captain following Latza's departure during the 2021–22 season, making him the youngest captain in the [[Bundesliga]].<ref>{{cite web|date=28 June 2024 |title=OL : que vaut réellement Moussa Niakhaté ? |url=https://www.footmercato.net/a8303867570736506440-ol-que-vaut-reellement-moussa-niakhate |website=footmercato.net}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

===Nottingham Forest===
In July 2022, he moved to the [[Premier League]] by signing with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{cite web|date=6 July 2022 |title=Transferts : Moussa Niakhaté (Mayence) signe trois ans à Nottingham Forest |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Transferts-moussa-niakhate-mayence-signe-trois-ans-a-nottingham-forest/1342310 |website=lequipe.fr}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> In only his second match, he suffered a hamstring injury, with his absence expected to last several months.<ref>{{cite web|date=20 August 2022 |title=Nottingham Forest : Moussa Niakhaté absent pendant quelques mois ! |url=https://wiwsport.com/2022/08/20/nottingham-forest-moussa-niakhate-absent-pendant-quelques-mois/ |website=wiwsport.com}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> He eventually returned in March 2023 after more than five months on the sidelines, having missed over thirty matches in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web|date=17 March 2023 |title=Les coulisses du retour "INESPERE" de Moussa Niakhaté |url=https://www.seneplus.com/sports/les-coulisses-du-retour-inespere-de-moussa-niakhate |website=seneplus.com}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

He established himself as a reliable defender in the league and took part in thirty-seven matches over two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|date=4 July 2024 |title=L’international sénégalais Moussa Niakhaté s’engage jusqu’en 2028 |url=https://www.ol.fr/fr/actualites/l-international-senegalais-moussa-niakhate-s-engage-jusqu-en-2028 |website=ol.fr}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

===Lyon===
On 4 July 2024, he joined [[Olympique Lyonnais]]. He became the second most expensive player in the club's history, behind [[Orel Mangala]].<ref>{{cite web|access-date=4 July 2024 |author=Mathias Fayet |date=4 July 2024 |title=OL : Moussa Niakhaté est lyonnais ! (officiel) |url=https://www.onzemondial.com/ligue-1/ol-moussa-niakhate-est-lyonnais--officiel-897402  |website=[[Onze Mondial]]}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref><ref>{{cite web|access-date=4 July 2024 |author=David Hernandez |date=4 July 2024 |title=Mercato : Niakhaté signe 4 ans à l’OL pour 31,9 millions d'euros |url=https://www.olympique-et-lyonnais.com/mercato-niakhate-signe-4-ans-a-lol-pour-319-millions-deuros,333663.html  |website=Olympique & Lyonnais}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> After a first season of adaptation, he established himself as a key figure in Lyon's central defense during the 2025–26 season. As one of the squad's vice-captains behind [[Corentin Tolisso]], he scored his first goal for Lyon on 27 November 2025, from a penalty against Israeli side [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]], contributing to a 6–0 victory for OL in the [[UEFA Europa League]].

== International career ==
Born in France, Niakhaté is [[Senegalese nationality law|Senegalese]] by descent. He is a former youth international for France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lasemaine.fr/fc-metz-10-choses-a-savoir-sur-moussa-niakhate-le-vent-de-fraicheur/|title=FC Metz : 10 choses à savoir sur Moussa Niakhaté, le vent de fraîcheur|first=Arnaud|last=Demmerlé|date=July 28, 2017}}</ref> He debuted with the senior [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]] in a 5–1 [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] win over [[Mozambique national football team|Mozambique]] on 24 March 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiwsport.com/2023/03/27/senegal-mozambique-ce-geste-de-moussa-niakhate-envers-les-stadiers/|title=Sénégal/ Mozambique : Ce geste de Moussa Niakhaté envers les stadiers|date=March 27, 2023}}</ref>

In December 2023, Niakhaté was named in Senegal's squad for the postponed [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]] held in the [[Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/67840713|title=Afcon 2023: Senegal and Sadio Mane set for defence of title|date=29 December 2023|access-date=29 December 2023|work=BBC Sport Africa}}</ref> In their round of 16 match against [[Ivory Coast national football team|the hosts]], he missed a penalty in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|shoot-out]] which Senegal lost 5–4 following a 1–1 draw after extra time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68052401|title=Afcon 2023: Senegal v Ivory Coast|work=BBC Sport |date=29 January 2024}}</ref>

